":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department for the fourth time in five days with progressively worsening abdominal pain and vomiting. At her first presentation, she was diagnosed with gastroenteritis and discharged with ondansetron. At subsequent presentations to different hospitals, this diagnosis was maintained and she was given oral rehydration advice, antiemetics and analgesia. She has a medical history of depression and takes sertraline. She does not smoke or drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears critically unwell. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. Her abdomen is distended and diffusely tender with generalised guarding and percussion tenderness. Blood tests reveal a white cell count of 22 x 10^9/L (4-11) and C-reactive protein of 320 mg/L (\u0026lt;5). A CT scan confirms a ruptured appendix with free fluid and generalised peritonitis. She undergoes an emergency open appendicectomy and requires admission to ICU post-operatively for sepsis management.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cognitive biases best explains the delay in this patient\u0027s diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Confirmation bias","Availability bias","Overconfidence bias","Premature closure","Diagnostic momentum"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case illustrates how an initial diagnosis can gain increasing momentum and acceptance over time, despite evidence that should prompt reconsideration. The patient presented multiple times with worsening symptoms, but the initial diagnosis of gastroenteritis was perpetuated until complications developed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiagnostic momentum\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when an initial diagnosis becomes increasingly fixed over time, with subsequent clinicians accepting the initial diagnosis without adequate critical review. In this case, the initial diagnosis of gastroenteritis influenced subsequent assessments at different hospitals, despite the emergence of signs suggesting appendicitis that ultimately progressed to perforation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConfirmation bias\u003C/strong\u003E involves seeking information that confirms existing beliefs while dismissing contradictory evidence. While this may have played a role, the main error was the perpetuation of the initial diagnosis despite multiple presentations with worsening symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOverconfidence bias\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when a clinician overestimates their own knowledge or ability, leading to diagnostic errors. While this may have contributed to individual assessments, the key error was the perpetuation of the incorrect diagnosis across multiple clinicians and encounters.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAvailability bias\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when clinicians make judgments based on easily recalled, recent, or dramatic cases rather than considering the full spectrum of possibilities. This is not the primary cognitive error demonstrated in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPremature closure\u003C/strong\u003E refers to accepting a diagnosis before it has been fully verified. While this may have occurred initially, the key error was the perpetuation of the incorrect diagnosis over multiple encounters despite clear evidence of deterioration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis case emphasises the importance of maintaining diagnostic flexibility and regularly reassessing working diagnoses, particularly when patients present multiple times with worsening symptoms. Multiple presentations should always trigger careful diagnostic review and consideration of alternative diagnoses.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Diagnostic momentum occurs when an initial diagnosis becomes increasingly fixed over time despite evidence that should prompt reconsideration.","Regular reassessment of working diagnoses is essential, particularly when patients are not responding to treatment as expected.","Multiple presentations with worsening symptoms should trigger careful diagnostic review."],"references":["Croskerry P. Achieving quality in clinical decision making: cognitive strategies and detection of bias. Acad Emerg Med. 2002;9(11):1184-204.","Saposnik G, Redelmeier D, Ruff CC, Tobler PN. Cognitive biases associated with medical decisions: a systematic review. BMC Med Inform Decis Mak. 2016;16(1):138.","O\u0027Sullivan ED, Schofield SJ. Cognitive bias in clinical medicine. J R Coll Physicians Edinb. 2018;48(3):225-32."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67898"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19293"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67898"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-31T08:14:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-31T08:16:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12027"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82796"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"17","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/17"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude07","name":"Bioethics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"18","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/18"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddd1\u200d\u2696\ufe0f","name":"Medicolegal","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":